I got into Civil War history this summer while riding up Latigo Canyon with @wcrtr after I asked him to hepl me make sense of this dangerous ganef meshuggener buffoon Trump and Will suggested reading Battlecry of Freedom, the definitive 900 page single volume on that moment. I plowed through it - definitely offers historical perspective on a split, confused, mentally unbalanced nation with profoundly unstable politicians, dramatically self-serving elected officials, heavy corruption, fist fights and cane beatings in Congress. A nation on the brink of self-immolation. In that remarkable story is a word appearing for the first time, used by Confederate soldiers who had enough, and just left the insanity to head home to find their families, form their own rebellions against the belligerents, and salvage what they could of their lives and their kin's lives. Skedaddle. Good word.

Brian Vernor/@vernor: I had the fortune to grow up riding bikes in Santa Cruz, CA. It's a famously rare place with amazing roads and trails right out your door. I barely got in a car until the day I drove away to college, and throughout my life lived in Santa Cruz, I've explored a seemingly endless network of roads and trails by bicycle. So grateful! This spot looks like roadie singletrack and it is, it's a ribbon of bike path that leads from the heart of the UCSC campus down to town. Every local mountain biker and road rider has been on this path countless times. Over the holidays I visited my hometown and got in as much riding as I possibly could in five days. Of course riding is beautiful in itself but being on a bike has lead me to experience a great depth of community around the world (literally), while nowhere do I experience that community more deeply than in Santa Cruz. Since OMATA is a new company and very aware of its roots I decided to use this instagram takeover to talk about my own cycling roots, indelibly tied to the people and land in Santa Cruz.
